David:

I created Foo.java, which simply has a main method that creates an exception object from the 3rd-party library and prints it out:

import com.esri.sde.sdk.client.*;
public class Foo { 
  public static void main(String[] args) { 
    System.out.println(&quot;Foo&quot;); 
    SeException ex = new SeWarningException(&quot;Testing&quot;);
    System.out.println(&quot;ex = &quot;+ex);
  } 
}

and a foo task in my build.xml

  &lt;target name=&quot;foo&quot; depends=&quot;compile&quot;&gt;
    &lt;java classname=&quot;Foo&quot; classpathref=&quot;test.classpath&quot; /&gt;
  &lt;/target&gt;

It does not exhibit the puzzling behavior.  I can run &quot;ant foo&quot; multiple times in succession without problems.  I added &quot;compile.tests&quot; to &quot;depends&quot; in the foo task, and it makes no difference (I can still run foo multiple times in a row without problems).

If I do this from the command line:
ant clean
ant test
ant test

I get a failure on the 2nd &quot;ant test&quot;.
If I do this:
ant clean
ant foo
ant test
ant foo

I get a failure on the &quot;ant test&quot; (ant compile and both runs of ant foo work fine).

compile.tests is this:

  &lt;target name=&quot;compile.tests&quot; depends=&quot;compile&quot;&gt;
    &lt;mkdir dir=&quot;build/classes&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;javac 
        srcdir=&quot;src_tests&quot; 
